@Node CONTENTS "SuperTags/QuickTags v2.53 Table of Contents"
@toc CONTENTS
What Is SuperTags?
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    If you're not familiar with a tagline program, basically what one does
is to take a short text comment and add it to the end of any text messages
you or your users create. This "tag" is located directly after the body of
the message, and can come either BEFORE or AFTER any signature files that
may exist.

    This program, however, is anything BUT "basic". Read on to find out
how to install this program into your bulletin boards.

   @{" INSTALLING FOR FIRST TIME      " link INSTALL}    @{" UPGRADING FROM SUPERTAGS V2.51/2 " link UPGRADE251}
   @{" UPGRADING FROM SUPERTAGS V2.50 " link UPGRADE250}    @{" UPGRADING FROM SUPERTAGS V2.11   " link UPGRADE}
   @{" HOW DOES SUPERTAGS WORK?       " link WORK}    @{" WHAT SHOULD I NOT DO YET?        " link NOTYET}
   @{" GETTING MORE SUPERTAGS SPEED   " link SPEED}    @{" OTHER INFORMATION OF NOTE!       " link INFO}
   @{" SUPERTAGS ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS     " link THANKS}    @{" CONTACTING THE AUTHOR; DOTORAN   " link DOTORAN}
@endnode
@Node INSTALL "How to INSTALL SuperTags/QuickTags v2.53 for the FIRST time!"
@toc CONTENTS

How Do I Install It?
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  There are numerous steps you need to do to insure a proper installation
of this program, so take your time and you'll be done before you know it:

1: There are two main directories used by this program. One is the location
   for all command files, while the other is the location of the actual tag
   line listing files. 

   As given in this archive, the two directories used are:

        SuperTags/           (Where the COMMAND FILES are stored)
        SuperTags/TagData/   (Where the TAGLINE FILES are stored)

   If it's not a problem for you, I suggest you simply copy the SUPERTAGS
   directory right into your DOORS: path and be done with it, however if
   you'd like to store the files elsewhere, you may.

   For the remainder of this installation procedure, <path> will be used to
   designate the path you chose in this step. Please REPLACE the <path> with
   the appropriate path you chose here.

2: You should now use the "CleanUp" program, located within the "SuperTags/"
   directory to insure each user's mail directory doesn't contain an older
   version config file. You can load this file into a text editor and change
   the values of some variables to tell it what TO and what NOT to delete.
   By default, it will delete any existing "FTagPrefs" files, which are used
   by the ForceTag program, if you happened to be using that program prior
   to using SuperTags. If, after you've tried it for awhile, you decide you
   do not wish to use SuperTags anymore, edit the "st" variable within this
   file and it will also delete existing "_SuperTags" files it finds.

   You can run the CleanUp program, either by using one of those RUNA
   commands that lets you run ARexx doors(there's one included in this
   archive), or else manually adopting it into your DOORS area. It's an 
   ARexx PFile, so should be added as such.

   This cleanup process may take a couple minutes, depending on how many
   user accounts you have online.

3: Load your BBSTEXT file into a text editor, then ADD the following to the
   BEGINNING of lines 299, 400, 478 and 781. The changed lines should then
   look like these:

        299:    {#0<path>SuperTags/ST.Loader}\\n1Feedback filing...
                ^                            ^
            Control-Q                    Control-Y

        400:    {#0<path>SuperTags/ST.Loader}Post filing...
                ^
        478:    {#0<path>SuperTags/ST.Loader}Response filing...
                ^
        782:    {#0<path>SuperTags/ST.Loader}Edit complete.\\n1
                ^                                          ^
            Control-Q                                  Control-Y

  NOTE1: Line 782 applies ONLY to CNet, v4.37+, and NOT to v3.05c.

  NOTE2: It is NOT neccessary that you add this to ALL of the lines above.
         Only add it to those lines where you'd like the ability to add a
         tagline to.

4: Now add the following to the BEGINNING of lines 770 and 776 of your
   BBSTEXT file:

        770:    {#0<path>SuperTags/QWK 1}\\n1Processing: %s\\n1
                ^                        ^                `---> Control-Y
        776:    {#0<path>SuperTags/QWK 0}\\n1%d file(s) proc... etc.
                ^                        ^
            Control-Q                Control-Y

   These additions will DISABLE SuperTags in the event a QWK-Message Packet
   was uploaded, instead of SuperTags trying to add a tag to each and every
   message that comes out of the QWK packet.

   Save your BBSTEXT file.

5: Load your BBSMENU file into a text editor, then go to the bottom of Menu
   # 2; Available Everywhere and ADD these two lines:

        TAGS    `1- | {#0<path>SuperTags/Config}
        TAGSM   `31 | {#0<path>SuperTags/Maint}
                      ^
                  Control-Q

   The TAGS command should be given to ALL users whom you wish to be able to
   use taglines. The TAGSM command should ONLY be given to those users whom
   you wish to give MAINTENANCE access to, when using SuperTags.

   Save your BBSMENU file, then reload both text files by first selecting 
   your CNet Control Panel(by clicking it once), then press the RAMIGA-T 
   keystroke combination.

6: Now create the following NEW event. If using CNet, v4.37+, load up your
   CNet CRON and create the event as shown below: (3.05c version follows)

                 ID : SuperTags                      
            Port(s) : 0
       Execute Date : Tommorrow EARLY AM, like 03:30.
      Valid Minutes : 01:00
         Event Type : RunARexx
             Invoke : Immediate-UDump
             Status : Ready
      Unloaded Port : Ignore
            Command : <path>SuperTags/AMaint
       Repeat Every : 1 Days, 0 Hours, 0 Minutes
    Only Execute On : Check ALL SEVEN DAYS

    If running, v3.05c CNet, then load up CNet CONFIG, then click the button
marked "Events...". Create your event like the following:

        Command   : RunARexx
        Date      : Tommorrow
        Time      : 03:00:00                        (for 3 AM)
        Valid     : 01:00:00                        (between 3 Am to 4 Am)
        Args      : <path>SuperTags/AMaint
        Ports     : 0                               (whatever works for you)
        Type      : Immediate--force system idle
 Repeat Days      : 1                               (run once every day)
        HH:MM:SS  : 00:00:00
        Except    : No Checkmarks

   Remember to ADD the Event, BEFORE you hit the OK button, or else it
   WON'T be saved!

7: Because this program will take on the responsibility of appending a 
   user's Signature File to the message, it will be necessary for you to 
   DISABLE Signature Files in ALL of your CNet Message Bases. To do this, 
   follow a series of steps like these:

        - Use the "EL" command to globally edit all bases...
          (If running v4.37+, you could use the EL1- button to globally
            set the value in ALL bases, however remember that SuperTags
            does NOT work in FILE bases, so make sure you leave signatures
            enabled in these areas, so that CNet can take care of them in
            these instances.)
        - Press the "Other Flags..." (or "Edit other flags...") button...
        - Set the "No signatures" flag to YES. (This is located in the
            second column, seventh item from the top)

        - You will now have to enter ALL SUBDIRECTORIES you have set up in
          your BASE and repeat the above steps to insure CNET doesn't append
          ANY signatures.

   If you neglect to correctly do this step, you'll discover that if the
   user selects to have SuperTags display their signature, it will appear
   TWICE in the textual message, because BOTH SuperTags AND CNet will append
   a copy of the sig file to the message!

   NOTE: When using the TAGSM command, on the Toggle Screen, you should note
         a cyan colored checkmark next to EACH base under the "Use Sigs"
         column to insure ALL bases do, indeed, have their signatures turned
         OFF on their EL screen. Any bases where you note a checkmark does
         NOT exist under "Use Sigs", you should check the EL screen of.

   Because CNet currently has no way to disable signatures from appearing in
   personal mail or feedback messages, SuperTags will NOT attempt to append
   a signature to these items. It will let CNet do it instead. It should 
   also be noted that the signature will ALWAYS appear at the END of these 
   messages, even if you have the Sig Method set to BEFORE the tagline(Again,
   this is because CNET is appending the sig, not SuperTags!)

8: There is an LHA archive contained in the "supertags.lha" archive:

            <path>SuperTags/Help/help.lha

   You need to unpack(unLHA) this archive directly into the HELP/ directory.
   If you're not sure how to do this, you can type this command into an
   open CLI/Shell window:

    lha x <path>SuperTags/Help/help.lha <path>SuperTags/Help/
       | |                             |
       `-^----- SPACES ----------------'

   NOTE: There are ONLY THREE spaces in this line. Do not include others!

9: If you'd like some more Taglists to add to your copy of SuperTags, and
   you haven't already done so, you can also opt to download one or more of
   the "supertag_pack?.lha" archives, which should be available through the
   same location you found the "supertags.lha" archive. These archives will
   contain the most up to date group of lists I have available(as of this
   writing, over 100 lists!). To add these lists into your system, simply
   unpack these archives directly into your TAGDATA/ directory, using a
   command like this:

    lha x downloads:supertag_pack1.lha <path>SuperTags/TagData/
       | |                            |
       `-^----- SPACES ---------------'

  NOTE1: There are ONLY THREE spaces in this line. Do not include others!

  NOTE2: Replace "downloads:" with the path where the taglist archive can
         be located.

  NOTE3: There are FIVE available "supertag_pack?.lha" archives, which each
         contain 25 additional taglists, so you should have QUITE a variety
         to choose from.

   You can now use the SuperTags Maint module to ADOPT these new lists into
   your system! Enjoy!

That's It! You're Done!

@{" Continue Through Document " link WORK}
@endnode
@Node UPGRADE251 "How to UPGRADE from SuperTags, v2.51 or v2.52"
@toc CONTENTS

How to Upgrade from v2.51 or v2.52?
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    To update from 2.51 or 2.52, copy ALL files located in this new archive 
OVER the existing ones in YOUR designated SuperTags/ directory. It is NOT 
neccessary for you to replace the TagLines or !STags.cfg files. Make sure 
to also copy the Update253 file into your /SuperTags/ directory as well.

    Once the copying is done, run the Update253 script from within CNet Amiga
proper, perhaps using one of those RUNA commands. This script will update the
Version Number of your !STags.cfg file.

    That's it! You're done!

@{" Continue Through Document " link WORK}
@endnode
@Node UPGRADE250 "How to UPGRADE from SuperTags, v2.50"
@toc CONTENTS

How to Upgrade from v2.50?
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    To update from 2.50, copy ALL files located in this new archive OVER the
existing ones in YOUR designated SuperTags/ directory. It is NOT neccessary
for you to replace the TagLines or !STags.cfg files. Make sure to also copy
the Update251 file into your /SuperTags/ directory as well.

    Once the copying is done, run the Update251 script from within CNet Amiga
proper, perhaps using one of those RUNA commands. This script will update the
!STags.cfg, TagLines, and all _SuperTags files that exist on your system.

    That's it! You're done!

@{" Now UpGrade to v2.53 " link UPGRADE251}
@endnode
@Node UPGRADE "How to UPGRADE from SuperTags, v2.11"
@toc CONTENTS

How to Upgrade from v2.11?
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   Note, that you MUST be running v2.11 to do the upgrade. NO EARLIER STags
versions are supported with these conversion steps!

1: Run the included "Update250" script. This script will do three things:

    a. Convert CTRL-A characters in "_SuperTags" files located in your
       mail:users/#?/ directories to | (Pipe Symbols).

    b. Do the same CTRL-A to | (Pipe) conversion to the "TagLines" file,
       located in your "SuperTags/" directory.

    c. Copy the "SuperTags.cfg" file INTO the "SuperTags/" directory, then
       rename it to "!STags.cfg". In addition, the same CTRL-A to | (Pipe)
       conversion will take place. The 2nd and 3rd lines of this file will
       also be REMOVED from this file, as these pertained to the storage
       paths, which are now being grabbed internally. A NEW value will also
       be added to the "new" third line of this file to hold the Maximum #
       of tags you're willing to allow each user to have in their Chosen Tags
       Listing. (by default, 200 will be used, but you can change this to
       any value between 20 and 999 from within the MAINT file).

2: You should now COPY ALL FILES FOUND IN THIS ARCHIVE ON TOP OF THE OLDER
   2.11 VERSION FILES YOU ARE PRESENTLY USING!

   NOTE: Existing taglists will be replaced with newer versions, while any
         unique taglists you may have are left intact.

  NOTE2: The <NEW> dupe checking routines in v2.50 resulted in almost EVERY
         taglist LOSING at LEAST 1, and more often MANY, duplicate tags, so
         it would be to your ADVANTAGE to replace the ones you have NOW with
         the updated ones in this archive.

3: There is one LHA archive contained in the "supertags.lha" archive:

            <path>SuperTags/Help/help.lha

   You need to unpack(unLHA) this archive directly into the HELP/ directory.
   If you're not sure how to do this, you can type this command into an
   open CLI/Shell window:

    lha -m x <path>SuperTags/Help/help.lha <path>SuperTags/Help/
       |  | |                             |
       `--^-^----- SPACES ----------------'

   NOTE: There are ONLY FOUR spaces in this line. Do not include others!

   NOTE: The "-m" option turns off interactivity, so that files contained
         within the archive will automatically REPLACE files with the same
         name that may already exist on your system.

4: If you'd like some more Taglists to add to your copy of SuperTags, and
   you haven't already done so, you can also opt to download one or more of
   the "supertag_pack?.lha" archives, which should be available through the
   same location you found the "supertags.lha" archive. These archives will
   contain the most up to date group of lists I have available(as of this
   writing, over 100 lists!). To add these lists into your system, simply
   unpack these archives directly into your TAGDATA/ directory, using a
   command like this:

    lha x downloads:supertag_pack1.lha <path>SuperTags/TagData/
       | |                            |
       `-^----- SPACES ---------------'

  NOTE1: There are ONLY THREE spaces in this line. Do not include others!

  NOTE2: Replace "downloads:" with the path where the second archive can
         be located.

  NOTE3: There are FIVE available "supertag_pack?.lha" archives, which each
         contain 25 additional taglists, so you should have QUITE a variety
         to choose from.

   You can now use the SuperTags Maint module to ADOPT these new lists into
   your system! Enjoy!

5: That should be it! Please, if I neglected to remember anything, please
   let me know ASAP! :-)

That's It! You're Done!

@{" Now UpGrade to v2.51 " link UPGRADE250}
@endnode
@Node WORK "How does SuperTags/QuickTags WORK exactly?!?"
@toc CONTENTS

How's It Work?
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   I suggest, once you've completed the installation process above, that you
try out the two commands TAGS and TAGSM. The TAGS command will load the
SuperTags Config program. This is the file all users have access to.  Once
loaded, hit the letter "H" for HELP on how to use that program. I won't
discuss it in this file.

    The TAGSM command loads the SuperTags Maintenance Module. This is the
file you'll use to change different settings for each of the included tag
lists, as well as adding NEW lists or deleting OLD lists. Use the "S"can
command to totally re-read the files located in the "TagData/" directory.

    The Maint Module also uses a HELP SYSTEM similar to the one used in the
main Config file. Press "H" once you're in the maintenance module to get
more help on what the different commands within that file do.

    The AMaint module looks for the existence of files ending in ".new" in
the "TagData/" directory. If found, they are then appended to the base tag
list, then sorted, dupe checked and a new copy of both the index and data
file are produced.

@{" Continue Through Document " link NOTYET}
@endnode
@Node NOTYET "Read the following, before playing inside the TagData/ Directory!"
@toc CONTENTS

What Should I NOT Do?
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    Do NOT add any other files to the "TagData/" directory, until AFTER you
have read the following paragraphs:

    There are three types of files located in the "TagData/" directory:

<filename>        - This is the MAIN TagLine Data File. It is a standard
                    text file, containing one tagline per line. The lengths
                    of tags should not exceed 78 characters.

<filename>.ndx2   - This is the index file for the above main tagline data
                    file. It holds the START location for each tagline found
                    in the main file, WITHOUT having to pad out each tagline
                    with a set number of spaces. This keeps the SIZE of the
                    main tagline data file from becoming HUGE. The index
                    also stores data pertaining to which letters tags start
                    with, as well as which tag to use next randomly.

<filename>.new    - Contains user added taglines, which will be added to the
                    main file above during next run of automaintenance.

    When you use the "S"canDir command in Maint, this directory is scanned
and ALL FILENAMES that do NOT end in ".ndx2" or ".new" will be taken to be
data files containing taglines. To add a list of your own tags, create the
data file, one tag per line, each NOT to exceed 78 characters, then copy it
to the "TagData/" directory. You can then use the "A"dd command to add just
that one NEW tagline listing. The accompanying ".ndx2" file will then be
created by the Maint file itself. The ".new" files are deleted each night
during automaintenance, so you shouldn't be seeing these files very often.

    If you'd like to edit one of the existing tagline lists, simply load it
into a text editor and make whatever changes you deem appropriate, HOWEVER,
you must REBUILD the Index File for this list AFTER you have saved it back
to disk. This MUST be done, REGARDLESS of what changes you made. By this, I
mean that even if all you do is slightly change the wording of one of the
taglines, the Index File STILL needs to be rebuilt, because unlike the text
file BBSTEXT, not only does the NUMBER of lines matter, but the LENGTH of
each line matters. The Index File is created BASED ON the LENGTH of each
line, AS WELL as how many taglines are found in the listing.

    Lastly, keep in mind that the FILENAME you use for any given tag list
will ALSO be the name the user see's most often when using SuperTags, so
you should name the file appropriately.

@{" Continue Through Document " link SPEED}
@endnode
@Node SPEED "What you can do to get more SPEED out of SuperTags v2.53?!?"
@toc CONTENTS

Getting More Speed Out Of SuperTags?
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    Depending on the number of lists defined, and the number of tags found
in the list to be used, it could take up to 5 seconds for SuperTags to do
all of it's work.

    Some more changes were made internally to decrease this time even more,
if it was found that the Tags were not to be used with this message, but
there are a couple things you can choose to do yourself to help keep the
speed up:

    - The MORE lists you offer your users, the SLOWER SuperTags will be.

    - Try to encourage your users to create the Custom Chosen Lists settings,
      instead of choosing from ALL the lists. If you offer 50+ lists, but
      the users choose only 5 of them, the speed increase will be shown even
      more.

    - Lastly, if they can do it, encourage the users to ONLY use the CHOSEN
      TAGS listing(the finite (20-999) item list). This is the FASTEST way 
      to use SuperTags as it only has to choose from the specific number of
      tags found within the user's Chosen List.

    - As of SuperTags, v2.11, the users have the ability to use QuickTags. 
      This is by far the FASTEST way to use SuperTags, so encourage users to 
      pick their favorite list, then activate QuickTags, if speed poses a 
      problem for them while online(perhaps for your Long Distance users)

    Someone asked about copying the lists to RAM: for more speed accessing
the tags. You really won't see much of an increase if this were done, because
of the way the program locates the tags. The index file allows SuperTags to
jump directly to a specified tagline, WITHOUT having to wade through all the
tags found before it. Doing it this way will only give you a slight increase
in speed, as jumping to a point in RAM versus HD is a miniscule leap in
performance. (Besides, by the time the computer finished copying the taglist
to RAM, it would already have found the tagline it needed on HD!)

    Keep in mind all the things that the SuperTags module has to do, before
it can successfully add a tagline. A large majority of these "checks" are not
performed when using the QuickTags(as they're not needed in QuickTags), which
is what makes QuickTags just that; QUICK!

@{" Continue Through Document " link INFO}
@endnode
@Node INFO "Other Information you might like to read about SuperTags v2.53!"
@toc CONTENTS

Other Information Of Interest?
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    The "dupe-checking" routine I'm using is a bit unique. It has the ability
to catch dupes of tags that use the identical wording, yet might use some
additional spacing or punctuation. For instance, these two tags are DUPES of
one another:

        FEE!  FI!  FO!  FUM!   "I smell the BLOOD of an Englishman!".

Fee-Fi-Fo-Fum; I smell the blood of an Englishman.

    Basically, what I'm doing is the following:

 1: Strip ALL preceeding AND trailing blanks.
 2: Remove all punctuation symbols.
 3: Remove all spaces between words.
 4: Convert entire string to uppercase.
 5: Save these "stripped" tags to a 2nd file, along with their index value.
 6: Alphabetically SORT this 2nd created file, then read back into memory.
 7: NOW, compare the two strings, and if identical, set the 1st one to NULL.
 8: Repeat the comparisons until finished, then resave this 2nd file.
 9: Alphabetically SORT this updated 2nd file and read into memory again.
10: Now compare this 2nd array to the 1st array, creating a 3rd file by
    saving any tag that is NOT a NULL tag.
11: Delete the 1st and 2nd files, renaming the 3rd file as the 1st.
12: Create a NEW index file for this NEWLY dupe-checked file.

So, the above two tags would look like this:

FEEFIFOFUMISMELLTHEBLOODOFANENGLISHMAN

FEEFIFOFUMISMELLTHEBLOODOFANENGLISHMAN

Which would then equate as a duplicate, upon which the latter is discarded.

   While not 100% foolproof, it DOES catch numerous dupes that DO pop up
that would not be caught if using a simple "100% match" type of checking,
of which the above two would NOT be considered duplicates.

    Steps 5 thru 12 are NEW as of v2.50 of SuperTags. These added steps allow
SuperTags to now catch additional dupes which may exist, like this one:

....Good things come to those that wait!

Good Things Come To Those That Wait...

    At first, these may look to be the same tag, however within the original
listing, the first appears near the TOP of the tag list, because it starts
with a period(certain punctuation symbols are located ABOVE the letters of
the alphabet within the Ascii Character value table), while the second would
be filed under the "G"'s in the list.

    Using the original pre-2.50 Dupe Checking, these tags WERE identical,
however because they sat in different locations within the listing, they
were NOT weeded.

    Once stripped of it's punctuation, the above two tags, when sorted in
steps 5 thru 7, now sit directly atop one another, and thus one can now be 
thrown out as a duplicate.

    There are still a few instances of tags which are "similar" but not
exactly duplicates, for instance those tags which use different spellings of
a word, like their and thier, or where a NAME is used, like James Kirk vs.
Jim Kirk, etc. but attempting to write code that would catch "dupes" of this
type is well beyond the scope of this program!

